{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18426"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114225"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11144"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114225"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following percentages best represents the optimal length for muscle contraction relative to resting muscle length?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u00b1 20%","\u00b1 10%","\u00b1 50%","\u00b1 30%","\u00b1 90%"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe length of a muscle influences the tension that its fibres can generate. The optimal length allows for the maximum number of cross-bridges to form between actin and myosin filaments, resulting in the greatest tension during contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe optimal length for muscle contraction is typically within \u003Cstrong\u003E\u00b1 10%\u003C/strong\u003E of the resting muscle length. This range allows for the best overlap between actin and myosin filaments, maximising the number of cross-bridges that can form and thus the tension that can be generated. When the muscle is at its normal resting length, which is at a sarcomere length of about 2 micrometers, it contracts on activation with the approximate maximum force of contraction. However, the increase in tension that occurs during contraction, called active tension, decreases as the muscle is stretched beyond its normal length\u2014that is, to a sarcomere length greater than about 2.2 micrometers. If the muscle is stretched or shortened beyond this range, the overlap is less optimal, and the tension generated decreases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The optimal length for muscle contraction is typically within 10% of the resting muscle length.","Optimal overlap of actin and myosin filaments allows for maximum cross-bridge formation and tension generation.","Muscle tension decreases if the muscle is stretched or shortened beyond the optimal length range."],"references":["Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:48:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:48:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11144"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114225"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i